the central government on friday 
dissolved the legislative assembly of oppositionruled karnataka 
state and put the state under federal rule news reports said 
federal home minister buta singh told parliament the move in the 
southern state came after the janata dal party lost its majority 
the reports said 
by law a new state assembly must be elected within a year 
the press trust of india news agency said singhs announcement 
was made amid protests from opposition members 
janata dal headed by former defense minister vp singh held 
111 of the 222 seats in the house it also was supported by seven 
independent members 
buta singh said the party lost its majority after 19 legislators 
withdrew support he said gov p venkatsubbiah reccomended 
dissolution of the assembly to president ramaswamy venkataraman 
pti quoted karnataka chief minister sr bommai as saying he had 
the support of 120 members in the house 
bommai leader of the janata dal party in the state said wide 
opposition would arise if the assembly was dissolved pti reported 
from bangalore the capital of karnataka 
the federal government is led by prime minister rajiv gandhi of 
the congress party 
