<TEXT>
the names of dissident priest gleb yakunin and 
four other announced candidates were removed friday from a ballot 
for the new soviet parliament a colleague reported 
yakunin a russian orthodox priest and the four were blocked 
from the ballot in a central district in moscow on grounds they 
didnt live or work in the district said victor popkov a 
christian activist who attended the district meeting at the zil car 
factory 
soviet election laws have no residency requirements many of 
those already elected to the new congress of peoples deputies were 
selected by organizations they did not belong to or from districts 
where they do not reside 
popkov said about 750 electors were at the district meeting and 
he said they were picked in a crude move on the part of the top 
echelon of the communist party 
he said the head of the central election commission agreed to 
meet saturday with yakunin and the other rejected candidates to 
hear their complaints 
none of the five was allowed to present his platform at the 
meeting and no election commission member was present to count the 
votes popkov said in a telephone interview 
yakunin was suspended from his religious duties for 20 years and 
imprisoned for dissident activities after more than six years in 
prison and exile in siberia he was released in march 1987 and 
assigned to a small parish near moscow 
popov said the four other rejected candidates were two writers 
a criminal investigator and a military officer the names of 11 
candidates were placed on the district ballot 
