<TEXT>
more than a third of the firstgrade boys 
in rural north carolina have tried smokeless tobacco and the 
number increases to 70 percent by seventhgrade a study shows 
the recent university of north carolina at asheville study found 
that the most frequently stated reason for using smokeless tobacco 
was its taste followed by peer pressure a desire to feel grown 
up and the influence of role models such as athletes 
the study used children in grades one three five and seven in 
urban and rural schools in western north carolina 
it was apparent during the administration of our questionnaire 
that the firstgraders clearly understood what oral tobacco was 
said cheryl mcclary coauthor of the study in two of the rural 
schools several little boys immediately jumped up to show their 
containers of chewing tobacco which they kept in their back 
pocket 
state law allows a 6yearold to buy and use smokeless tobacco 
but prohibits the sale of cigarettes or cigarette papers to anyone 
under 17 
</TEXT>
