<TEXT>
relatives of americans killed in the bombing 
of pan am flight 103 say they are encouraged by recent government 
response to aviation security problems but still want a broad 
investigation into the incident 
transportation secretary samuel skinner on friday announced 
rejection of calls for an independent commission to look into the 
dec 21 bombing he then took off for europe to meet with 
transportation officials in five countries 
bert ammerman spokesman for relatives of nearly 200 americans 
killed in the explosion over lockerbie scotland expressed 
disappointment with the decision saying we feel theres enough 
information thats been uncovered that only an independent 
investigation can deal with appropriately 
ammermans brother tom was killed in the bombing 
among concerns of the relatives are the lack of a public warning 
of threats against the flight security procedures that failed to 
detect the plastic explosive which authorities say was believed 
planted by terrorists and inadequate government response after the 
incident 
ammerman of demarest nj said however there have been 
several positive developments since the relatives staged a rally 
and met with bush and other officials in washington on april 3 
including steps to improve aviation security he said the state 
department had agreed to escort relatives who want to visit 
lockerbie 
skinner was meeting in naples italy this weekend with the 
administrations nominee to head the federal aviation 
administration adm james b busey who is us navy commander for 
europe and next week with government and airline officials in 
italy west germany switzerland france and england 
skinner in a news conference for foreign journalists covering 
washington said he would push for security initiatives that would 
encourage international travelers to retain their justified 
confidence in the systems safety 
skinner said us carriers have given unbelievable attention 
to security and are the safest in the world 
his spokesman david prosperi said skinner and other 
transportation and security officials were flying most of the way 
on a government plane to meet a tight schedule but would likely 
make at least part of the trip aboard commercial airliners 
skinner in a letter to ammerman rejecting the call for a 
separate investigation said for a variety of reasons we do not 
believe formation of an independent commission is necessary or 
prudent the letter was accompanied by a fivepage outline of 
administration action since the pan am explosion 
skinner said he had confidence in the investigation by scottish 
and west german authorities and the fbi and believed those 
responsible for planting the bomb which investigators have said 
was hidden in a radiocassette will be apprehended and prosecuted 
i can assure you that in my opinion the investigation is 
moving at full speed skinner said i think that eventually and 
hopefully in the not too distant future the public will know the 
full story there he said it was important not to disclose 
targets of the investigation or the information being sought 
skinner said his trip would review screening given foreign 
nationals hired by us airlines abroad and seek diplomatic 
approval for installation of devices to detect plastic explosives 
in airports used by us carriers abroad 
