<TEXT>
health and human services secretary louis w 
sullivan gave his approval friday to a plan by federal scientists 
to wipe out tuberculosis in the united states by the year 2010 
i challenge you at cdc to carry out the strategies necessary 
to accomplish that goal sullivan said in a speech to employees 
at the centers for disease control 
the contagious lung disease attacked more than 22000 americans 
last year 
tb can be cured in most cases with drug therapy but has become 
a growing public health problem in recent years in part because of 
the spread of aids which weakens the immune system allowing tb 
among other diseases to develop scientists estimate that about 10 
million americans are infected with tb bacteria but the vast 
majority never get the disease 
the advisory committee for the elimination of tuberculosis 
created by the department of health and human services in 1987 
calls for more effective use of existing prevention and control 
programs development of new diagnosis and treatment techniques 
and rapid transfer of new technology into widespread medical use 
sullivan who was president of atlantas morehouse school of 
medicine before being appointed secretary of hhs by president bush 
also visited the new national headquarters of the american cancer 
society across the street from the cdc compound 
