firefighters quelled a brush fire that 
erupted friday over 1200 acres of the pike national forest and 
forced the evacuation of more than 200 homes in scattered 
subdivisions near colorados foothils authorities said 
there were no reports of injuries or of damage to houses said 
craig a coultas spokesman for the woodmoormonument fire 
protection district 
about 175 firefighters from 20 agencies converged on the area 
about 20 miles north of colorado springs after the blaze broke out 
shortly after noon in the mount herman estates in unincorporated 
el paso county he said 
we do have it under control with 20 to 30 spot fires within 
the perimeter he said on saturday he said firefighters would 
overhaul the fire and finish the job the cause of the blaze was 
unknown he said 
coultas said structures in three subdivisions were evacuated in 
front of the fire burning grass brush scrub oak and pines 
the terrain has given us more fits than anything else 
coultas said fire tends to move up and so its following the 
contours of the land moving up the side of the mountain 
an air tanker was dropping fire retardant on the periphery of 
the blaze and helicopters were pulling water from monument lake to 
drop on the fire another air tanker was en route from arkansas to 
join the fire fighting 
officials said the rough terrain also was preventing workers 
from bringing in bulldozers to build fire lines so axes and small 
hoses were being used 
el paso county sheriffs spokesmen predicted it would take three 
or four days to quench the fire 
the national weather service said colorados rangeland fire 
danger was extreme as record high temperatures were reported 
friday in eastern colorado and the fire danger was high in the 
mountains 
