<TEXT>
more than 100000 students peacefully left 
tiananmen square on saturday after staging 15 hours of protests 
demanding democracy and an end to dictatorship in china 
student leaders decided to withdraw from the square at about 
145 pm 1245 am saturday after officials reopened the square 
to ordinary crowds that had swelled by the tens of thousands and 
become increasingly unruly 
earlier the students raising their fists and chanting long 
live freedom confronted the chinese leadership as they filed 
into a memorial service for ousted party leader hu yaobang in the 
great hall of the people beside the square 
the death of hu 73 from a heart attack last saturday has 
sparked massive student protests 
the students saturday afternoon marched out of the square waving 
colored banners calling for democracy and chanting arise 
citizens 
traffic was stopped along changan boulevard the capitals main 
avenue and people climbed trees to get a better view of the 
procession 
the students said they would go back to their campuses and begin 
a boycott 
they shouted down with dictatorship again and again 
demonstrators filled a street dividing the square from the great 
hall which was guarded by a triple line of peoples liberation 
army soldiers 
party general secretary zhao ziyang hus successor delivered a 
10minute address at the memorial service he said hu worked 
unswervingly for the party and marxist ideals during his 60year 
revolutionary career 
about 4000 mourners led by senior leader deng xiaoping and 
members of the politburo attended the ceremonies 
hus body was draped in the red flag of the communist party 
most of the mourners wore mao jackets and trousers but hu was 
dressed in a western suit 
zhao made no specific mention about hus ouster but said he was 
a man brave enough to admit his mistakes and to insist upon what 
he thought was right he never tried to hold back his own 
opinions 
zhao praised hus unusual courage and resourcefulness in 
redressing the wrongs done to intellectuals and other citizens 
during the radicals 196676 cultural revolution 
deng xiaoping 84 walked around the casket and shook hands with 
hus wife 
the student rallies have filled tiananman square since monday 
and are much larger than prodemocracy demonstrations in the winter 
of 198687 that led to the ouster of hu an outspoken reformist 
long live democracy long live freedom down with bureaucracy 
down with corruption the students chanted as the officials 
entered the great hall 
the students also yelled severely punish strongarmed 
tactics a reference to purported police beatings of some 
students during a clash in front of the nearby communist party 
headquarters thursday morning 
chinese observers said the overnight demonstration on the square 
was one of the largest of its kind ever since the communist victory 
over the nationalists in 1949 
tens of thousands of students from about 30 universities many 
bearing wreaths for hu and prodemocracy banners streamed into the 
square about friday midnight where up to 100000 people had 
congregated during a day of rallies 
the students gathered in circles centered around a wreathladen 
monument to revolutionary heroes and sang eulogized hu and held 
debates about democracy 
some outspokenly criticized the communist system no one 
believes in communism anymore said one 34yearold teacher no 
one believes in the party the party is strangling china 
ren wanding activist in the shortlived 1978 democracy wall 
period of relative tolerance for democratic views told one 
audience of about 2000 people are praying for the awakening of 
a legal system this is a historical necessity democracy wall 
lives again 
others critized deng xiaoping for holding onto power and 
demanded that premier li peng resign saying he lacked ability for 
the job 
at about 615 am saturday a student leader announced to 
cheers that the authorities agreed to let the students remain in 
the square while the party memorial service took place in the great 
hall 
the beijing government on friday announced that access to the 
great hall and the square would be restricted during the ceremony 
students feared police or soldiers would move in during the night 
to drive them out of the area 
a victory for us a big victory the communist party has 
backed down said one jubilant student in the square 
the students acknowledged however that authorities rejected a 
list of demands presented earlier in the week 
they included more funding for education public disclosure of 
the incomes of top leaders and an end to the ban on unauthorized 
demonstrations 
students said the most significant demand was for greater press 
freedom a persistent theme during the demonstrations 
the official press has given little coverage to the 
demonstrations except to report on alleged violent acts by 
demonstrators during thursdays clash and issue warnings that those 
taking advantage of hus death to promote antigovernment 
activities will be punished 
tiananmen square a 100acre plaza sided by the forbidden city 
the great hall and mao tsetungs mausoleum is the symbolic center 
of china 
saturdays demonstration was the biggest since april 1976 when 
the death of premier chou enlai sparked a huge outpouring of grief 
and anger toward the leftist government 
that tiananmen incident set off events that were to lead to 
the overthrow of the leftists and the end of the 196676 cultural 
revolution 
hu was widely admired by students for his work in redressing the 
wrongs done to intellectuals during that decade of chaos 
he was ousted as party leader in january 1987 after party 
conservatives accused him of being soft on student demonstrators 
and the trend toward bourgeois liberalization 
on saturday one government worker in the demonstration said of 
deng our leader is old maybe he is crazy many people hope he 
will die 
deng remains popular for his marketoriented reforms that have 
brought china some economic prosperity but he has carried out only 
limited political reforms and does not tolerate opposition to 
oneparty rule 
deng who was believed at one point to have chosen hu as his 
successor approved hus ouster after prodemocracy demonstrations 
rocked the nation in december 1986 and january 1987 
