<TEXT>
two military space shuttle flights 
planned next summer will be delayed one for at least three months 
because work on the shuttle columbia is taking longer than expected 
nasa said friday the schedule had become too tight to support 
both missions and still preserve an october launch for the 
highpriority galileo flight to jupiter 
a discovery launch that had been scheduled for aug 10 will be 
delayed until at least november columbia which had a july 1 
launch target will be launched in early august the space agency 
said 
both missions are to deploy classified defense department 
payloads 
unaffected will be fridays planned liftoff of atlantis with the 
magellanvenus spacecraft on board the first planetbound payload 
scheduled for release from a space shuttle 
the schedule changes will have a ripple effect on launch dates 
later in the year leaving nasa with six instead of its goal of 
seven shuttle launches this year 
officials have said the planned oct 12 liftoff of atlantis with 
the jupiterorbiting galileo spacecraft is a highpriority flight 
because there is only a 40day launch period during which jupiter 
and earth are aligned properly so it will be next in line after 
columbias august mission 
then will come the delayed discovery military flight probably 
in november and a flight probably in december in which 
columbias crew is to deploy a communications satellite and 
retrieve a science satellite which has been orbiting since 1984 
the mission of discovery with the hubble space telescope long 
awaited by astronomers will slip from its present december launch 
slot into 1990 
nasa said dates for missions after the galileo flight will be 
determined later 
nasa management has become increasingly concerned that the 
work involved in preparing the orbiter columbia for its first 
flight in over three years is taking long enough that it might 
endanger the option to launch galileo at the opening of the launch 
window said shuttle chief richard h truly our overriding 
objectives in this situation are to protect the galileo window and 
to fly columbia as early as we can 
following the challenger explosion in january 1986 the shuttle 
fleet was grounded for 32 months while the three remaining orbiters 
underwent major modifications to improve safety and performance 
the modified discovery has made two flights since the accident 
