bellmon wearing a cowboy hat and a westernstyle jacket and other 
dignitaries looked on 
speeches on the library steps delayed the start of the parade 
past its scheduled noon start 
mayor james weems got 65 floats and 18 marching bands rolling 
around 1215 pm drawing cheers from a crowd estimated at 50000 
as he said weve waited 100 years for this so lets start this 
sucker 
most of the settlers who flocked here in 1889 were immigrants 
former civil war soldiers blacks and farmers fleeing drought they 
also were opportunists speculators and profiteers 
edmond author stan hoig a retired central state university 
professor who has written 10 books on oklahoma history said the 
land run proved to be unfair at the time many called the 
unprecedented event harrisons hoss race 
for some the race was not to the swift but to the sneaky the 
sooners who got in sooner than everyone else and gave the state 
its nickname evaded federal troops guarding the areas borders and 
claimed choice parcels disputes over sooner claims snarled the 
courts for years 
those who staked claims for homesteads faced five years of hard 
work to prove up their land and gain permanent ownership many 
lived in houses constructed of sod cut from thickly matted soil 
that had never felt a plow 
some gave up their claims only to try again at later land 
openings in the indian territory four more via runs others by 
lottery allotment and sealed bids 
guthrie swelled by settlers staking their claims became the 
territorial capital and was the state capital before oklahoma city 
took its place in 1910 
