<TEXT>
thousands of gallons of water 
flooded a control room at the river bend nuclear power plant 
knocking out pumps that help cool the reactor a nuclear regulatory 
commission spokesman said saturday 
the plant had been shut down for about three weeks for refueling 
and maintenance when the accident occurred shortly after midnight 
wednesday said bill benedetto spokesman for plant owner gulf 
state utilities 
the reactor cores temperature never exceeded 95 degrees there 
were no injuries and the pumps were working again within 10 minutes 
of the accident benedetto said 
a federal investigative team arrived friday to look into the 
accident said nrc spokesman joe gilliland 
according to gilliland a maintenance crew had been fixing a 
6inch water pipe in the plants auxiliary building which houses 
pumps and control centers workers used seals to block water to the 
section the crew was working on but the seals failed and about 
15000 gallons poured out 
the pipe carries water used to cool various plant equipment but 
not the reactor itself gilliland said the water that spilled was 
not radioactive 
however the flood shorted out electrical equipment running the 
pumps that cool the reactor and powering lights in several parts of 
the plant benedetto said 
he said the work that caused the spill would not have been 
performed if the reactor had been operating 
the inspection teams report should be completed in about three 
weeks about the same amount of time river bend is to remain shut 
down gilliland said 
river bend is about 25 miles northwest of baton rouge and has 
been in operation since 1985 
